Given the quantum model
$$f(x) = \langle \psi(\theta)| \sigma_z| \psi(\theta)\rangle$$
with
$$| \psi(\theta)\rangle = R_x(\theta) | 0\rangle, \;\; R_x(\theta) = e^{-i \theta \sigma_x }$$
and
$$\sigma_z = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix}, \; 
\sigma_x = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}.
$$ 
How can we estimate $\frac{\partial f}{\partial \theta} $ with a quantum computer?

$$ \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\theta} = \\frac{\\partial }{\\partial \\theta} \\langle 0 | e^{i \\theta \\sigma_x} \\sigma_z e^{-i \\theta \\sigma_x} |0 \\rangle $$\n$$ = \\langle 0 | (i \\sigma_x) e^{i \\theta \\sigma_x} \\sigma_z e^{-i \\theta \\sigma_x} |0 \\rangle - \\langle 0 | e^{i \\theta \\sigma_x} \\sigma_z (-i \\sigma_x) e^{-i \\theta \\sigma_x} |0 \\rangle$$ \n$$ = i \\left( \\langle 0 | \\sigma_x e^{i \\theta \\sigma_x} \\sigma_z e^{-i \\theta \\sigma_x} |0 \\rangle + \\langle 0 | e^{i \\theta \\sigma_x} \\sigma_z \\sigma_x e^{-i \\theta \\sigma_x} |0 \\rangle \\right)$$
